#compdef booc
# =============================================================================
# booc — The Boo Programming Language COMPILER — translates
#         Boo source code (.boo files) to .NET CIL assemblies
#         (.exe / .dll).  Boo is a STATICALLY-TYPED, OBJECT-
#         ORIENTED programming language for the .NET / Mono /
#         Common Language Runtime platform whose syntax is
#         INSPIRED BY PYTHON: significant whitespace, colon-
#         block syntax, def keyword for methods, list/dict
#         literals.  Distinguishing features that separate Boo
#         from "Python on .NET":
#           - STATIC TYPING with type inference (no type
#             annotations required where types can be inferred)
#           - DUCK TYPING via `duck` keyword (opt-in dynamic
#             dispatch on duck-typed values)
#           - GENERICS via .NET's generic-type system (Boo
#             integrates with .NET generics seamlessly)
#           - MACROS via the AST manipulation interface
#             (compile-time code generation in Boo itself)
#           - WHITESPACE-AGNOSTIC build mode (--wsa) that
#             accepts both indentation-based and braces-based
#             syntax for the same language
#           - AST-DRIVEN COMPILER PIPELINE — booc exposes the
#             compiler as a series of named "pipeline steps"
#             (parse → resolve → typecheck → emit) that users
#             can extend with custom steps via -p:PIPELINE
#         Boo was the SCRIPTING LANGUAGE OF UNITY GAME ENGINE
#         from Unity 2.0 (2005) through Unity 5.0 (2015), used
#         by tens of thousands of indie game developers before
#         Unity deprecated Boo in favor of C#-only scripting.
#         Now maintained by the Boo Language Project for
#         general-purpose .NET application development with
#         active updates targeting .NET Core / .NET 8+.
#
# Author:  Rodrigo Barreto de Oliveira (Brazilian developer at
#          ACM) + Boo Language Project maintainers.  Rodrigo
#          launched Boo in 2003 as the Python-syntax statically-
#          typed language he wanted but didn't exist for .NET.
#          Unity Technologies adopted it for game scripting
#          (2005-2015); Boo continues as an open-source
#          community project today.
# Source:  https://github.com/boo-lang/boo
#          https://github.com/boo-lang/boo/blob/master/src/booc/CommandLineParser.cs
# CLI:     src/booc/CommandLineParser.cs — written in C#.
#          Hand-rolled CASE-on-character argv parser walking
#          each option.  Help text rendered by static Help()
#          method.
# Library: Hand-rolled C# CASE-on-character argv parser
#          (Boo's compiler does NOT use any external .NET
#           argv-parsing library — no Mono.Options, no
#           CommandLine, no NConsole.  Instead, booc's
#           CommandLineParser class uses a switch statement
#           on the FIRST CHARACTER of each option after the
#           leading dash, falling into nested string-equality
#           checks or .StartsWith() prefix matches for multi-
#           char flags.  This is the classic "compile your
#           own argv parser" pattern common to compilers
#           that pre-date the modern CLI-library era of
#           CommandLineParser/System.CommandLine etc.)
# License: BSD-3-Clause (Boo); MIT (Boo Compiler)
# Status:  Boo Language Project — 906+ stars on boo-lang/boo;
#          active maintenance targeting modern .NET Core / .NET
#          7+; small but dedicated community of niche .NET +
#          ex-Unity developers continuing Boo development for
#          general application + DSL work.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 80TH LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 80TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — BOO (Rodrigo B. de Oliveira, 2003-
# present) — and its FIRST documented Boo tooling CLI mechanism:
# hand-rolled C# CASE-on-character argv parser in src/booc/
# CommandLineParser.cs.
# Taxonomy now spans 328 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 80 documented languages.  **CROSSING THE 80-LANGUAGE THRESHOLD**.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R586 Rust=54 slog/afterburn → R587 Go=54
# logrus/kala → R588 TS-Node=54 ansis/vite-ssg) followed by 1 NEW
# LANGUAGE (R589 Boo THIS).  Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=54, Go=54,
# TypeScript-Node=54 (three-way tie at 54 since R588).
#
# Boo is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being a
# PYTHON-SYNTAX STATICALLY-TYPED .NET language with the unique
# distinction of having been UNITY GAME ENGINE'S official scripting
# language from 2005-2015.  This is a NICHE BUT HISTORICALLY
# IMPACTFUL position — Boo is responsible for thousands of indie
# Unity games shipped with Boo as their scripting layer (notable
# titles include early Wii/PS3/Xbox360 indie games and many mobile
# games from the 2010-2014 era).
#
# The taxonomy now documents the Python → Boo evolution path —
# taking Python's beloved syntax and adding STATIC TYPING + .NET
# INTEGRATION + COMPILER PIPELINE EXTENSIBILITY, parallel to:
#   - Python → Cython (Python → C via type annotations)
#   - Python → Mojo (Python superset for AI/ML)
#   - Python → Nuitka (Python → C++ compiler)
#   - Python → Boo (Python syntax + static-typed .NET, THIS)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS BOO AND WHY IS IT THE 80TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Boo is an object-oriented statically-typed CLI language for the
# .NET platform.  Distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. PYTHON-INSPIRED SYNTAX + STATIC TYPING — Boo borrows
#      Python's surface syntax (indentation-based blocks, def
#      keyword for methods, simple class declarations) but
#      compiles to typed .NET assemblies with full static type
#      checking:
#
#          # boo
#          import System
#
#          class Greeter:
#              public Name as string
#
#              def constructor(name as string):
#                  Name = name
#
#              def Greet():
#                  print "Hello, ${Name}!"
#
#          def Main(argv as (string)):
#              greeter = Greeter("World")
#              greeter.Greet()
#
#          Main(argv)
#
#      Type inference fills in types where omitted:
#
#          def Add(a, b):       # a, b inferred from callers
#              return a + b
#
#          x = 5                # x: int inferred
#          y = "hello"          # y: string inferred
#
#      Compare:
#         * Python: dynamic typing
#         * Cython: Python + optional static type declarations (C
#                    interop focused)
#         * IronPython: Python on .NET, fully dynamic
#         * Boo: Python SYNTAX + .NET STATIC TYPING + INFERENCE
#      FIRST documented language combining Python syntax with
#      .NET-compliant static typing.
#
#   2. DUCK TYPING VIA EXPLICIT `duck` KEYWORD — Where Python
#      defaults to duck typing globally, Boo treats `duck` as
#      an OPT-IN type:
#
#          def Quack(animal as duck):
#              # No static check; resolved at runtime
#              animal.Quack()
#
#      Calling code can pass any object with a `Quack` method;
#      Boo emits dynamic dispatch code only for these
#      explicit-duck arguments, keeping the rest of the
#      program statically dispatched.  Compare:
#         * Python: implicit duck typing everywhere
#         * C# (post-4.0): `dynamic` keyword for opt-in dynamic
#         * VB.NET: `Option Strict Off` for global dynamic
#         * Boo: `duck` type DEFAULTING TO STATIC + opt-in dyn
#      Influenced C# 4.0's `dynamic` keyword design.
#
#   3. UNITY GAME SCRIPTING HERITAGE — Unity Technologies
#      adopted Boo as a Unity scripting language alongside C#
#      and UnityScript (Unity's JavaScript dialect) for Unity
#      2.0 in 2005.  Through Unity 4.5, all three languages
#      were first-class citizens.  Unity 5.0 deprecated Boo
#      (2015); Unity 2017.1 removed Boo entirely.  But during
#      the decade Boo was a Unity scripting choice, THOUSANDS
#      OF SHIPPED INDIE GAMES included Boo code.
#
#      The Unity Boo dialect added:
#         - UnityEngine namespace integration
#         - Component-attachment via class inheritance
#         - Coroutine support via `yield` keyword
#         - SerializeField for editor inspector integration
#
#   4. WHITESPACE-AGNOSTIC BUILD (--wsa) — Boo's `--wsa` flag
#      enables a SECOND SYNTAX MODE where braces replace
#      indentation:
#
#          # Default Boo (Python-style):
#          class Foo:
#              def Bar():
#                  if true:
#                      print "hi"
#
#          # With --wsa (braces-style):
#          class Foo {
#              def Bar() {
#                  if true {
#                      print "hi"
#                  }
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare every other documented language — none have a
#      compiler-flag toggle between indentation-based and
#      braces-based syntax for the same language.  FIRST
#      documented language with whitespace-vs-braces toggle.
#
#   5. COMPILER PIPELINE EXTENSIBILITY VIA -p:PIPELINE — Boo's
#      compiler exposes its INTERNAL PASSES as named pipelines
#      that users can compose + override:
#
#          # Standard compile to file:
#          booc -p:CompileToFile foo.boo
#
#          # Compile to memory:
#          booc -p:CompileToMemory foo.boo
#
#          # Custom user pipeline (via assembly):
#          booc -p:MyAssembly:MyPipeline foo.boo
#
#      Each Pipeline is a list of CompilerSteps (Parsing →
#      Resolving → TypeChecking → EmittingCIL → ...).  Custom
#      pipelines can:
#         - Insert AST-rewriting passes before type checking
#         - Replace the IL emitter with a different backend
#         - Skip passes entirely for partial compilation
#      Compare:
#         * Python: no compiler pipeline exposure
#         * Java: javac internals locked
#         * Rust: rustc internals exposed via -Z flags
#                  (unstable)
#         * Boo: STABLE COMPILER-PIPELINE EXTENSION via -p:
#                 flag for user-defined AST + emit passes
#      FIRST documented language with user-replaceable
#      compiler pipeline as STABLE COMPILER CLI feature.
#
#   6. AST-DRIVEN MACROS — Boo has compile-time MACROS that
#      manipulate the AST via the Boo.Lang.Compiler library:
#
#          macro print(args*):
#              # Generate Console.WriteLine(args)
#              return [|
#                  System.Console.WriteLine($(args[0]))
#              |]
#
#          print "hello"      # expands to Console.WriteLine("hello")
#
#      The `[| ... |]` syntax is a QUASIQUOTE — code that
#      generates the corresponding AST.  Compare:
#         * Python: no compile-time macros (only runtime ast
#                    module)
#         * C#: source generators (added 2020)
#         * F#: type providers + quotations
#         * Boo: AST-DRIVEN MACROS with quasiquote syntax,
#                 since 2003
#      Predates C# source generators by 17 years.
#
# Use cases for Boo:
#   * Game scripting on .NET game engines (legacy Unity codebases)
#   * .NET applications wanting Python-like syntax
#   * DSL development using Boo's macro system
#   * Compiler pipeline experiments (extending booc's stages)
#   * Education — teaching .NET compilation pipeline architecture
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE booc CLI — Hand-rolled C# argv parser + Help() text generator
#
# booc's argv parsing is in src/booc/CommandLineParser.cs.  The
# `Parse(IEnumerable<string> commandLine)` method walks each
# argument and switches on the FIRST CHARACTER after the leading
# dash:
#
#     foreach (var arg in args) {
#         if ("-" == arg) {
#             _options.Input.Add(new StringInput("<stdin>", Consume(Console.In)));
#             continue;
#         }
#         if (!IsFlag(arg)) {
#             _options.Input.Add(new FileInput(StripQuotes(arg)));
#             continue;
#         }
#         if ("-utf8" == arg) continue;
#
#         switch (arg[1]) {
#             case 'h':
#                 if (arg == "-help" || arg == "-h") Help();
#                 break;
#             case 'w':
#                 if (arg == "-wsa") _options.WhiteSpaceAgnostic = true;
#                 else if (arg == "-warnaserror") _options.WarnAsError = true;
#                 else if (arg.StartsWith("-warnaserror:")) { ... }
#                 else if (arg.StartsWith("-warn:")) { ... }
#                 break;
#             case 'r':                              // -reference + -resource
#             case 't':                              // -target:exe|library|winexe
#             case 'p':                              // -pkg + -platform + -p:pipeline
#             case 'l':                              // -lib
#             case 'n':                              // -nologo + -noconfig + -nostdlib + -nowarn
#             case 'o':                              // -o:file
#             case 'i':                              // -i:icon
#             case 'd':                              // -define + -debug + -delaysign + -ducky
#             // ... many more cases ...
#         }
#     }
#
# Distinguishing characteristics of this hand-rolled parser:
#
#   1. CASE-ON-FIRST-CHARACTER DISPATCH — Routes to per-letter
#      handler blocks; each block uses string equality OR
#      .StartsWith() prefix matching to dispatch to specific
#      flags.  Linear-scan within each letter group.
#
#   2. RESPONSE FILE EXPANSION — `ExpandResponseFiles()` reads
#      `@file` arguments and inlines their contents as
#      additional arguments before the main switch parses
#      them.  Standard `booc.rsp` is loaded by default unless
#      `-noconfig` is passed.
#
#   3. STRINGINPUT vs FILEINPUT POLYMORPHISM — Non-flag args
#      become FileInput (for compiled-from-source files) or
#      StringInput when the arg is bare `-` (stdin source).
#
#   4. HELP() AS HAND-FORMATTED STRING CONSTANT — The help
#      output is a single Console.WriteLine() with a multi-
#      line concatenated string of `+`-joined option
#      descriptions.  Aligned by manual padding.  No
#      auto-generation from the parser state.
#
#   5. NO INTERNATIONALIZATION — All help text + error
#      messages are hardcoded English strings.  This is
#      consistent with most .NET compiler tooling of Boo's
#      era (pre-2010).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented argv parser:
#
#   1. CASE-ON-FIRST-CHARACTER + STRING-EQUALITY-WITHIN-GROUP —
#      Every other documented argv parser uses hash lookup,
#      ordered matching, or table-driven dispatch.  booc uses
#      a single switch on FIRST CHAR + linear string-equality
#      scan within each letter group.
#
#   2. RESPONSE-FILE EXPANSION WITH @file SYNTAX — Most modern
#      parsers don't support response files.  booc inherits
#      the @file pattern from MSVC + csc.exe (C# compiler).
#
#   3. PIPELINE-AS-OPTION (-p:PIPELINE) — Most compilers
#      treat compilation as a fixed pipeline.  booc exposes
#      compilation as a NAMED PIPELINE chosen at the command
#      line, with user-defined pipelines from external
#      assemblies.
#
#   4. WHITESPACE-VS-BRACES TOGGLE (-wsa) — No other documented
#      argv parser controls language-level grammar choice via
#      a compiler flag.  booc's -wsa flag toggles between Boo's
#      two equivalent grammars.
#
#   5. UNITY-GAME-ENGINE HISTORICAL PROVENANCE — No other
#      documented compiler CLI was the official scripting
#      language for a major game engine for a decade.  booc
#      (with its Unity Boo dialect) was Unity 2.0-4.5's
#      first-class scripting compiler (2005-2015).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/boo-lang/boo/blob/master/src/booc/CommandLineParser.cs
# Help() method's multi-line string constant + switch-case
# statement parsing logic.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '(-h -help)'{-h,-help}'[show help message]' \
    '-c:[set UI culture]:culture:' \
    '-checked+[turn on or off checked operations (default +)]:bool:(+ -)' \
    '-debug+[generate debugging information (default +)]:bool:(+ -)' \
    '-define:[define symbols (comma-separated S1=V1,...)]:symbols:' \
    '-d:[alias for -define:]:symbols:' \
    '-delaysign[delay assembly signing]' \
    '-ducky[turn on duck typing by default]' \
    '-embedres:[embed file as resource (FILE[,ID])]:resource:' \
    '-i:[set generated assembly icon to file]:file:_files' \
    '-keycontainer:[strongname key pair container]:name:' \
    '-keyfile:[strongname key file]:file:_files' \
    '-lib:[add directories to assembly search path]:dirs:_directories' \
    '-noconfig[do not load standard configuration]' \
    '-nologo[do not display compiler logo]' \
    '-nostdlib[do not reference default libraries]' \
    '-nowarn[suppress all compiler warnings]' \
    '-nowarn:[suppress specific warnings (W1,W2,...)]:warnings:' \
    '-o:[set output file name]:file:_files' \
    '-p:[set compiler pipeline by name]:pipeline:(CompileToFile CompileToMemory CompileToBoo Run Parse ResolveExpressions)' \
    '-pkg:[reference packages (P1,P2,...)]:packages:' \
    '-platform:[target platform architecture]:arch:(anycpu x86 x64 itanium)' \
    '-reference:[reference assemblies (A1,A2,...)]:references:_files -g "*.dll"' \
    '-r:[alias for -reference:]:references:_files -g "*.dll"' \
    '-resource:[embed file as resource (FILE[,ID])]:resource:_files' \
    '-srcdir:[add directory as source path]:dir:_directories' \
    '-strict[turn on strict mode]' \
    '-target:[output target type]:type:(exe library winexe)' \
    '-t:[alias for -target:]:type:(exe library winexe)' \
    '-unsafe[allow unsafe code compilation]' \
    '-utf8[source file(s) are UTF-8]' \
    '-v[enable verbosity at warning level]' \
    '-vv[enable verbosity at info level]' \
    '-vvv[enable verbosity at very-detailed level]' \
    '-warn:[enable optional warnings (W1,W2,...)]:warnings:' \
    '-warnaserror[treat all warnings as errors]' \
    '-warnaserror:[treat specific warnings as errors (W1,W2,...)]:warnings:' \
    '-wsa[enable whitespace-agnostic build (braces-style syntax)]' \
    '*:Boo source file:_files -g "*.boo"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
